This results in even numbers on the die. - If the first roll is even, all even numbers are halved. This results in odd numbers on the die. 3. **Probability of Second Roll Being 2**: - After the first roll, the die will have either all even or all odd numbers. - If the first roll was odd, the die will have even numbers, including potentially more instances of 2. The probability of rolling a 2 depends on the number of 2s in the modified die. - If the first roll was even, the die will have odd numbers, so the probability of rolling a 2 is zero. 4. **Final Calculation**: - After the first roll, the probability that the second roll is 2 is calculated as: - \( P(\text{second roll is 2}) = P(\text{first roll odd}) \times P(2 \text{ on second roll} | \text{first roll odd}) + P(\text{first roll even}) \times P(2 \text{ on second roll} | \text{first roll even}) \) - Given the die modifications, if the first roll is odd, the probability increases, and if even, it decreases. **Answer**: The probability that a 2 will appear on the second roll of the die is \( \boxed{\dfrac{1}{9}} \).
